{
  "Atomic radius generally decreases across a period because:": "",
  "Neutrons are added": "",
  "Atoms lose electrons": "",
  "Increasing nuclear charge pulls electrons closer": "",
  "Electrons are farther away": "",
  "Each element across a period adds a proton and an electron in the same shell. The added protons increase nuclear charge without adding shielding, pulling all electrons inward and shrinking the atom.": "",
  "Ionization energy generally increases across a period because:": "",
  "Electrons are farther from the nucleus": "",
  "Atoms get bigger": "",
  "Electrons are held more tightly by increasing nuclear charge": "",
  "Neutrons increase": "",
  "As effective nuclear charge (Zeff) increases across a period, electrons are bound more tightly. It takes more energy to pull an electron away from a smaller, more positively charged nucleus.": "",
  "Electronegativity increases:": "",
  "Only across a period": "",
  "Only down a group": "",
  "Going down and to the left": "",
  "Going up and to the right on the periodic table": "",
  "Smaller atoms with higher Zeff attract bonding electrons more strongly. Fluorine (top-right, excluding noble gases) has the highest electronegativity (3.98 on the Pauling scale).": "",
  "Which element has the largest atomic radius?": "",
  "Neon (Ne)": "",
  "Francium (Fr)": "",
  "Helium (He)": "",
  "Fluorine (F)": "",
  "Francium is at the bottom-left of the periodic table, where atomic radius is greatest. It has 7 electron shells and low nuclear charge per shell, making it the largest atom.": "",
  "Which element has the highest electronegativity?": "",
  "Cesium (Cs)": "",
  "Fluorine is the most electronegative element (EN = 3.98). Its small size and 7 valence electrons give it an extremely strong pull on bonding electrons. Noble gases are excluded since they rarely bond.": "",
  "Going down a group, atomic radius:": "",
  "Decreases": "",
  "Stays the same": "",
  "Increases": "",
  "Varies randomly": "",
  "Each row down adds a new principal energy level (shell). More shells mean the outermost electrons are farther from the nucleus, so atomic radius increases down a group.": "",
  "Going down a group, ionization energy:": "",
  "Doubles": "",
  "Going down, valence electrons are farther from the nucleus and more shielded by inner electrons. They are easier to remove, so ionization energy decreases. Cesium has one of the lowest IE values.": "",
  "Which of these has the highest first ionization energy?": "",
  "Sodium": "",
  "Helium": "",
  "Cesium": "",
  "Potassium": "",
  "Helium (top-right) has the highest first ionization energy of all elements (2372 kJ/mol). Its 2 electrons are in the 1s orbital, very close to 2 protons with no shielding.": "",
  "Metallic character increases going:": "",
  "Up and to the right": "",
  "Equally in all directions": "",
  "Down and to the left": "",
  "Metals lose electrons easily. Going down and left, atoms have lower ionization energy and fewer valence electrons, making them more metallic. Francium would be the most metallic element.": "",
  "Electron affinity generally becomes more negative (more energy released) going:": "",
  "Across a period from left to right (with exceptions)": "",
  "Down a group": "",
  "It doesn't follow any trend": "",
  "Toward the bottom-left": "",
  "Halogens (Group 17) have the most negative electron affinities because gaining one electron completes their octet. Chlorine has the most negative EA (-349 kJ/mol) due to its optimal size.": "",
  "What is ionization energy?": "",
  "The minimum energy required to remove an electron from a gaseous atom in its ground state": "",
  "The distance from nucleus to outermost electron": "",
  "The energy an atom gives off when forming bonds": "",
  "The charge of the nucleus": "",
  "Ionization energy (IE) measures how tightly an atom holds its electrons. First IE removes the most loosely held electron; second IE removes the next, and so on. Successive IEs always increase.": "",
  "What is electronegativity?": "",
  "The ability of an atom to attract shared electrons toward itself in a chemical bond": "",
  "The charge of an anion": "",
  "The total number of electrons in an atom": "",
  "The energy needed to remove an electron": "",
  "Electronegativity (Pauling scale) measures electron-attracting ability in bonds. The difference in EN between two bonded atoms determines bond polarity: >1.7 = ionic, 0.4–1.7 = polar covalent, <0.4 = nonpolar.": "",
  "What is atomic radius?": "",
  "The number of electron shells": "",
  "The distance electrons travel": "",
  "Half the distance between the nuclei of two bonded identical atoms": "",
  "The size of the nucleus": "",
  "Since atoms don't have sharp boundaries, atomic radius is measured as half the internuclear distance (bond length) in a homonuclear diatomic molecule (e.g., Cl–Cl). Covalent and van der Waals radii are different measures.": "",
  "What is electron affinity?": "",
  "The speed of an electron": "",
  "The energy change when an electron is added to a neutral gaseous atom": "",
  "The number of electrons lost": "",
  "How much an atom likes other atoms": "",
  "A negative electron affinity means energy is released when an electron is gained (exothermic). A positive EA means energy must be added. Noble gases have positive EA — their full shells resist gaining electrons.": "",
  "What is metallic character?": "",
  "The distance from the nucleus to the outermost electron shell, which increases going right across a period": "",
  "The tendency of an element to lose electrons and exhibit properties of metals (luster, conductivity, malleability)": "",
  "The total mass of all electrons in the atom, which increases as more sublevels become occupied with electrons": "",
  "The charge of the nucleus divided by the number of neutrons, known as the nuclear density ratio": "",
  "Metallic character relates to how easily atoms lose electrons to form cations. Elements with low ionization energy and few valence electrons (like alkali metals) are most metallic.": "",
  "What is a periodic trend?": "",
  "The energy needed to add an electron to a neutral gaseous atom, which decreases as atomic number increases": "",
  "A trend that only applies to metals": "",
  "The energy released when a neutron is removed from the nucleus of an atom in the gas phase state": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all electrons orbiting the nucleus, measured in kilojoules per mole": "",
  "Periodic trends emerge because electron configuration follows a repeating pattern. Elements in the same group have similar valence electron arrangements, giving them similar properties.": "",
  "What is the second ionization energy (IE₂)?": "",
  "Twice the first ionization energy": "",
  "The energy needed to remove a second electron from an already singly-ionized atom (X⁺ → X²⁺)": "",
  "The electron affinity of the ion": "",
  "The energy to remove two electrons at once": "",
  "IE₂ is always greater than IE₁ for the same element because the remaining electrons experience more nuclear charge. For Na, IE₂ is dramatically higher (4562 vs 496 kJ/mol) because it removes a core electron.": "",
  "What does it mean when noble gases have positive electron affinity?": "",
  "An atom’s ability to lose electrons in a chemical bond, which increases as you move across a period to the right": "",
  "They have no electrons": "",
  "The tendency of an atom to repel shared electrons in a covalent bond toward the other bonded atom": "",
  "The number of electrons an atom must gain to achieve a noble gas configuration in ionic bonding": "",
  "Noble gases have completely filled outer shells. Adding another electron would require starting a new, higher-energy shell. This process is energetically unfavorable, so their EA is positive (endothermic).": "",
  "Why does nitrogen have a higher ionization energy than oxygen?": "",
  "It increases because each new shell is farther from the nucleus and electrons experience less attraction": "",
  "It stays the same because all elements in a group have the same number of valence electrons": "",
  "Oxygen is smaller": "",
  "It follows no trend because atomic radius depends only on the mass of neutrons in the nucleus": "",
  "This is an exception to the general trend. Nitrogen (2p³) has each 2p orbital singly occupied, giving extra stability. Oxygen (2p⁴) must pair one electron, causing repulsion that makes it easier to remove.": "",
  "What is the ionic radius of Na⁺ compared to neutral Na?": "",
  "It increases from left to right because each added electron shields the others from nuclear charge": "",
  "It remains constant across a period since all atoms in the same row have the same energy levels": "",
  "Much smaller — losing an electron removes the outer shell and increases the proton-to-electron ratio": "",
  "It fluctuates randomly with no predictable pattern because electron configurations vary unpredictably": "",
  "Na (186 pm) → Na⁺ (95 pm). Removing the single 3s electron eliminates the third shell entirely. Also, 11 protons now pull on only 10 electrons, drawing them closer.": "",
  "A student needs to predict which is more reactive: sodium or potassium. Using periodic trends, the answer is:": "",
  "It increases going down a group because inner electrons are closer to the nucleus and harder to remove": "",
  "Sodium — it is higher and closer to fluorine": "",
  "It remains constant within a group since all members have the same number of core electron shells": "",
  "It alternates between high and low values depending on whether the atomic number is even or odd": "",
  "Alkali metal reactivity increases down the group. Potassium's valence electron is farther from the nucleus, more shielded, and requires less energy to remove (419 kJ/mol vs 496 for Na).": "",
  "A chemist compares the reactivity of fluorine and iodine for gaining electrons. Which is more reactive and why?": "",
  "The energy required to remove a proton from the nucleus, which increases for heavier elements with more mass": "",
  "They are equal": "",
  "The energy needed to break a covalent bond between two atoms, which depends on bond order and length": "",
  "The energy released when an atom gains a neutron, measured in electron volts per nucleon in the atom": "",
  "For nonmetals (halogens), reactivity increases UP the group — opposite of metals. Fluorine's tiny size means electrons are added very close to the high nuclear charge, making it the most reactive nonmetal.": "",
  "An engineer needs to choose a material that resists corrosion (losing electrons). Using IE trends, which metal best resists corrosion?": "",
  "It increases going down a group because additional shells add more protons and increase the nuclear pull": "",
  "Gold — it has high ionization energy for a metal, making electron loss difficult": "",
  "It stays constant within a group because shielding and nuclear charge increase by the same amount": "",
  "It decreases going down because heavier atoms have stronger gravity pulling electrons toward the nucleus": "",
  "Gold's high IE (890 kJ/mol) and filled d-subshell make it extremely reluctant to lose electrons. This is why gold doesn't tarnish or corrode — it resists oxidation in air and most acids.": "",
  "In a hospital, oxygen is more electronegative than carbon. What does this explain about the CO₂ molecule?": "",
  "Noble gases have the highest electronegativity because their full outer shells attract electrons very strongly": "",
  "Metals on the left side of the periodic table have the highest electronegativity due to their low ionization energy": "",
  "The C=O bonds are polar because oxygen pulls electron density toward itself, though the molecule overall is nonpolar due to symmetry": "",
  "Electronegativity is identical for all elements because every atom attracts electrons with equal electromagnetic force": "",
  "Oxygen (EN=3.44) vs carbon (EN=2.55) creates polar C=O bonds. However, CO₂ is linear and symmetric, so the two bond dipoles cancel, making the overall molecule nonpolar.": "",
  "A student observes that lithium reacts slowly with water while cesium explodes. Using periodic trends, this is because:": "",
  "Metallic character increases across a period because atoms gain more electrons and become better conductors": "",
  "Metallic character stays the same across a period since all elements in a row have the same energy levels": "",
  "Cesium has fewer protons": "",
  "Metallic character has no periodic trend and varies randomly depending on the isotope of the element": "",
  "Li IE = 520 kJ/mol; Cs IE = 376 kJ/mol. Cesium's 6th-shell electron is far from the nucleus, heavily shielded, and easily lost. This makes Cs explosive in water — producing CsOH + H₂ with violent exothermic energy.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher asks why magnesium (Mg) has a higher ionization energy than aluminum (Al). The explanation is:": "",
  "Francium (Fr) in the top-right corner of the periodic table has the highest metallic character of all elements": "",
  "Mg's 3s² is a filled sublevel which is more stable than Al's 3p¹, making Mg's electron harder to remove": "",
  "Carbon (C) in the center of the periodic table has the highest metallic character due to its four valence electrons": "",
  "Fluorine (F) at the top of Group 17 has the highest metallic character because it easily gains one electron": "",
  "This is another IE exception. Mg (3s²) has a complete s-sublevel that is extra stable. Al's 3p¹ electron is in a higher-energy sublevel and is easier to remove despite Al having one more proton.": "",
  "A materials scientist compares the ionic radii of O²⁻ and F⁻. Both have 10 electrons, but which is larger?": "",
  "Ionization energy and electronegativity both decrease across a period as atoms get larger and hold electrons loosely": "",
  "They are the same size": "",
  "Both properties stay constant across a period because the number of electron shells doesn’t change for elements": "",
  "They follow opposite trends — ionization energy decreases while electronegativity increases across each period": "",
  "In isoelectronic species (same electron count), the one with fewer protons has a larger radius. O²⁻ (8p, 10e) = 140 pm; F⁻ (9p, 10e) = 133 pm. Less nuclear pull means a more diffuse electron cloud.": "",
  "A researcher explains why chlorine has a more negative electron affinity than fluorine, despite fluorine being more electronegative. The reason is:": "",
  "They have very high ionization energies, making them extremely reactive with most other elements in nature": "",
  "Chlorine is more electronegative": "",
  "They have extremely high electronegativity values and readily form covalent bonds with all metal elements": "",
  "They are highly metallic elements that easily lose electrons to form large positive cations in solution": "",
  "Cl EA = -349 kJ/mol; F EA = -328 kJ/mol. Fluorine's extremely small 2p orbitals pack electrons so tightly that repulsion partially offsets the energy released. Chlorine's larger 3p orbitals accommodate the extra electron with less repulsion.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical chemist needs an element that readily forms a 2⁻ ion in drug compounds. Based on periodic trends, the best choice from Group 16 is:": "",
  "Tellurium — it is at the bottom of the group": "",
  "Polonium — it has the most electrons": "",
  "Any element works equally": "",
  "Oxygen — it has the highest electronegativity in the group, so it most readily gains 2 electrons": "",
  "Nonmetal reactivity increases up a group. Oxygen's small size and high EN (3.44) give it the strongest tendency to gain 2 electrons and complete its octet, forming O²⁻ ions (oxide) in many compounds.": "",
